PMC - PMC13155000
OAB - Slipping rib syndrome is a condition in which thelooseness of the rib joints 
      causes the lower ribs to move abnormally andirritate nearby nerves, leading to 
      chronic chest wall pain. Common treatmentsinclude pain medications, physical 
      therapy, and injections such as intercostalnerve blocks. When these approaches 
      are ineffective, surgery to stabilize theribs may be recommended. In this case 
      report, we describe a patient withchronic chest wall pain due to slipping rib 
      syndrome. She did not experiencelasting relief with opioid medications or other 
      standard treatments, andsurgery was recommended. To help manage her pain before 
      surgery, we performed a procedure called radiofrequency ablation, which works by 
      interrupting painsignals from the affected nerves. Following the procedure, the 
      patientexperienced significant pain relief and was able to begin decreasing her 
      opioidmedication. She later underwent rib fixation surgery and remained 
      pain-freeafter surgery. Overall, this case suggests that radiofrequencyablation 
      may play an important role in the care of patients with chronic chestwall pain.
