TI  - Rib fixation for flail chest physiology and the facilitation of safe prone spinal 
      surgery: illustrative case.
LID - CASE22337 [pii]
LID - 10.3171/CASE22337 [doi]
AB  - BACKGROUND: Spine fractures are frequently associated with additional injuries in 
      the trauma setting, with chest wall trauma being particularly common. Limited 
      literature exists on the management of flail chest physiology with concurrent 
      unstable spinal injury. The authors present a case in which flail chest 
      physiology precluded safe prone surgery and after rib fixation the patient 
      tolerated spinal fixation without further issue. OBSERVATIONS: Flail chest 
      physiology can cause cardiovascular decompensation in the prone position. 
      Stabilization of the chest wall addresses this instability allowing for safe 
      prone spinal surgery. LESSONS: Chest wall fixation should be considered in select 
      cases of flail chest physiology prior to stabilization of the spinal column in 
      the prone position. Further research is necessary to identify patients that are 
      at highest risk to not tolerate prone surgery.
