TI  - Penetrating pulmonary vein laceration following blunt chest trauma.
PG  - 100596
LID - 10.1016/j.tcr.2021.100596 [doi]
LID - 100596
AB  - Flail chest is a common injury in blunt trauma which is usually treated with 
      analgesia, oxygen, and other conservative measures. In more severe cases 
      mechanical ventilation and surgical stabilization of rib fractures (SSRF) may be 
      warranted. Penetrating injury to the heart or great vessels due to rib fractures 
      however, is much less common. Here we present a 33 year old male that was 
      admitted to the Emergency department (ED) after a horse riding accident, 
      demonstrating severe shock. Emergency computerized tomography scan showed 
      multiple bilateral displaced rib fractures, Left hemothorax and possibly a 
      penetrating injury to the left side of the heart by one of the ribs. Notably, no 
      significant pericardial effusion was demonstrated. In addition, a grade V splenic 
      injury was diagnosed. A Joined thoracic and abdominal emergent surgical treatment 
      was successfully carried out and the patient survived and fully recovered.
