IS  - 2397-5776 (Linking)
VI  - 4
IP  - 1
DP  - 2019
TI  - Minimally invasive chest wall stabilization: a novel surgical approach to 
      video-assisted rib plating (VARP).
PG  - e000366
LID - 10.1136/tsaco-2019-000366 [doi]
LID - e000366
AB  - The current morbidity of rib plating is due to the size of the incision required 
      to perform an open procedure. We describe a minimally invasive laparoscopic 
      approach to rib plating. A cadaver model was used to develop the surgical 
      technique by performing both left and right posterior-lateral rib plating. A 
      small incision was made over the auscultatory triangle. The potential working 
      space is developed under the posterior shoulder girdle and the scapula. A 
      table-based retractor was used to elevate the scapula and the muscles. Two 
      separate ports were placed: one camera port and one working port. In three 
      cadaver models, 12 rib fractures were plated and the surgical technique is 
      described. This novel technique will likely allow for faster recovery and was 
      especially useful in the subscapular space. Level of evidence II.
