TI  - A Case of Traumatic Flail Chest Requiring Stabilization with Surgical 
      Reconstruction.
PG  - 8-10
LID - 10.1055/s-0035-1558433 [doi]
AB  - Background Flail chest is the most serious complication that may occur after 
      thoracic trauma. In this article, we present a case of flail chest caused by 
      blunt chest trauma, which presented dramatic clinical improvement following rib 
      fixation and chest wall reconstruction. Case Description A 53-year-old male 
      patient with flail chest because of the trauma who had been followed in intensive 
      care unit for mechanical ventilatory support underwent chest wall stabilization 
      with titanium reconstruction plate and screws. Conclusion The main objective is 
      surgical stabilization of the chest wall in cases of flail chest with a 
      parenchymal damage because of the severe rib fracture, which need prolonged 
      mechanical ventilation.
