IS  - 1863-6713 (Electronic)
IS  - 1863-6705 (Linking)
VI  - 64
IP  - 9
DP  - 2016 Sep
TI  - Use of a titanium alloy (Chest Way) in the surgical stabilization of flail chest.
PG  - 561-3
LID - 10.1007/s11748-015-0549-4 [doi]
AB  - To avoid the complications of internal pneumatic stabilization for flail chest, 
      we performed stabilization of the chest wall with a metal bar using the Nuss 
      procedure. Here, we used a highly elastic lightweight biocompatible titanium 
      alloy Chest Way (Solve Corporation, Kanagawa, Japan), enabling magnetic resonance 
      imaging. The patient was a 37-year-old man who sustained injuries in a car crash. 
      Gradually increasing subcutaneous emphysema was present. Bilateral pleural 
      drainage and tracheal intubation were conducted on the scene, and a peripheral 
      venous line was established. The patient was then transferred to our hospital by 
      helicopter. A titanium alloy Chest Way was inserted to manage his flail chest 
      accompanied by multiple rib fractures on the left side. Two days later, 
      artificial respiration was no longer required.
