IS  - 1003-0034 (Linking)
VI  - 24
IP  - 3
DP  - 2011 Mar
TI  - [Treatment of complex scapular body fractures by locking reconstructive plates].
PG  - 253-5
AB  - OBJECTIVE: To investigate the method and effect of treatment of complex scapular 
      body fractures by locking reconstructive plate through modified posterior 
      approach. METHODS: From August 2005 to November 2009, 27 patients with complex 
      scapula body fractures were treated by locking reconstruction bone plate 
      fixation,including 19 males and 8 females with an average age of 36 years old 
      ranging from 16 to 64 years. The time after injury was 0.5 hours to 11 days 
      (averaged 3 days). Of all the patients, 9 cases were associated with ipsilateral 
      clavicle fracture, 2 cases were associated with acromioclavicular joint 
      dislocation,16 cases were associated with multiple rib fractures, 1 case were 
      associated with humeral shaft fractures, 5 cases were associated with pleural 
      effusion, atelectasis, lung contusion etc. After operating,shoulder functional 
      recovery were followed up. RESULTS: Twenty-four patients were followed up from 2 
      to 35 months with an average of 19 months. According to Hardegger shoulder 
      function,the results were excellent in 15 cases, good in 7 cases, general in 2 
      cases. CONCLUSION: This method had the advantage of less trauma and clear 
      exposure, firm and reliable fixation, and early activities.
