TI  - Scanning electron microscopic study of primary fracture healing.
PG  - 165-8
AB  - Scanning electron microscopy was used to study primary bone healing. This 
      technique, essential for a three-dimensional description, has provided excellent 
      visualization and revealed new aspects of the micromorphology of primary bone 
      healing. Calcifying collagen bundles were responsible for the first mechanical 
      stability, bone healing took place later in fracture vaults generated by 
      compressed fracture fragments which were partially nonvital. A direct bridging of 
      the fracture fragments by sprouting osteons was not observed.
