TI  - Rib fracture healing in experimental flail chest.
PG  - 903-8
AB  - Sixteen dogs were placed under general anesthesia and flail segments of the left 
      chest were created by transecting ribs 7,8,9, and 10 anteriorly and posteriorly. 
      Fractures were 10 cm apart so that a 10-cm flail segment encompassing four ribs 
      was created. In Group I, the control (N = 5), the chest wall muscles were closed 
      without any stabilization of the fractures. Group II (N = 5) had stabilization of 
      both anterior and posterior fracture sites by polypropylene sutures. Group III (N 
      = 6) had stabilization of the fractures in ribs 7 and 8 with 2.5-cm bone grafts 
      taken from the left fourth rib. Ribs 9 and 10 were stabilized by polypropylene 
      sutures. The study established a canine model for flail chest. It also showed 
      that strut stabilization of rib fractures with bone grafts promotes better 
      healing than suture stabilization. It suggests that using bone grafts taken from 
      another rib to stabilize flail segments may be unsatisfactory since the rib used 
      as a donor showed no signs of regeneration at 30 days.
